{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":15893,"record_hash":"sha256:66ce4e168d1767770b0d77eab625b26b95eb035ad6773af1a324fb3c19fbf1db","timestamp":"2026-05-09T18:33:02.249Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"I think the separation still makes sense, and it is not just bloat.\n\nThe key distinction is:\n\n```text\nTranscriptRecord\n  = parsed provider record, still in memory, pre-storage\n\nTranscriptEnvelope\n  = redacted GitMeta record, shaped for long-term storage\n```\n\nThe overlap is a little visually suspicious because the fields are similar, but they are on opposite sides of an important boundary:\n\n```text\nCodex/Claude JSONL\n  -> TranscriptRecord\n       raw parsed source_record\n       original record hash\n       extracted normalized fields\n\n  -> TranscriptEnvelope\n       source_key added\n       raw fields redacted\n       source_record redacted\n       storage field names\n       serialized into GitMeta\n```\n\nFor the two future use cases, that boundary matters. Handoff and PR sharing both depend on the GitMeta data being shareable and redacted. Keeping a separate stored shape makes it harder to accidentally persist parser/internal state.\n\nThe one thing that gives a tiny “AI shape” smell is the name `TranscriptEnvelope`. Now that we removed per-record `schema`, it is less of an “envelope” and more of a stored transcript item. A better name might be:\n\n```rust\nStoredTranscriptRecord\n```\n\nor maybe:\n\n```rust\nGitMetaTranscriptRecord\n```\n\nI would not collapse the two structs right now. If we want a cleanup, I’d rename `TranscriptEnvelope` to `StoredTranscriptRecord` and keep it private inside `gitmeta.rs`. That preserves the useful boundary while making the concept less abstract.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-09T18:33:02.249Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}